docs.abstract: President Trump held a campaign-style rally in Washington Township, Mich., forgoing the annual White House Correspondents’ Association dinner for the second consecutive year.
docs.snippet: President Trump held a campaign-style rally in Washington Township, Mich., forgoing the annual White House Correspondents’ Association dinner for the second consecutive year.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON TOWNSHIP, Mich. — President Trump capped a volatile week of progress and setbacks with a long, angry blast at Democrats, the news media, immigration laws and other favorite adversaries on Saturday night as he sought to reinforce his position as a Washington outsider victimized by a system threatened by him.

headline.main: In a Very Different Washington, Trump Unloads on a Litany of Adversaries
headline.print_headline: In Campaign-Style Rally in Michigan, Trump Blasts Critics and Pats Self on the Back

docs.abstract: It was the latest indication that President Trump is standing by his decision to impose a 25 percent tariff on steel imports and a 10 percent tariff on aluminum imports from all countries.
docs.snippet: It was the latest indication that President Trump is standing by his decision to impose a 25 percent tariff on steel imports and a 10 percent tariff on aluminum imports from all countries.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump warned on Saturday that he would apply higher taxes on imported European cars if the European Union carried through on its threat to retaliate against his proposed stiff new tariffs on steel and aluminum.

headline.main: Escalating Trade Fight, Trump Threatens Higher Taxes on European Cars
headline.print_headline: Trade War Escalates With Threat On E.U. Cars

docs.abstract: From the expulsion of Russian diplomats to a citizenship question on the 2020 census, here are five of the biggest stories driving U.S. politics this week, in a nutshell.

docs.lead_paragraph: Even with Congress on break, there was a lot of news this week. From the expulsion of Russian diplomats to a citizenship question on the 2020 census, here are five of the biggest stories in American politics this week, in a nutshell. headline.main: Let Us Catch You Up on the Biggest Stories in Politics This Week

docs.abstract: The president, at a rally for Montana’s Republican Senate candidate, also revived his “Pocahontas” attack on Senator Elizabeth Warren.
docs.snippet: The president, at a rally for Montana’s Republican Senate candidate, also revived his “Pocahontas” attack on Senator Elizabeth Warren.
docs.lead_paragraph: GREAT FALLS, Mont. — President Trump lobbed personal and derogatory attacks at two Democratic senators, mocked the #MeToo movement and vouched for President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia on Thursday during a freewheeling, raucous rally ostensibly intended to solidify support for Montana’s Republican Senate candidate.

headline.main: Trump Assails Critics and Mocks #MeToo. What About Putin? ‘He’s Fine’
headline.print_headline: President Assails Critics and Mocks #MeToo. What About Putin? ‘He’s Fine’

docs.abstract: “This place for me is for the birth of America, birth of liberty and, now, the birth of my citizenship,” said Joseph Csaba Nagy, formerly of Romania.
docs.snippet: “This place for me is for the birth of America, birth of liberty and, now, the birth of my citizenship,” said Joseph Csaba Nagy, formerly of Romania.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. — Just before 9 a.m. on the Fourth of July, the gong on Monticello’s roof rang, silencing the crowd that had gathered to celebrate those vowing to uphold and protect the ideals of the United States.

headline.main: Immigrants Take Oath at Monticello, Feeling the Weight of the Past
headline.print_headline: Immigrants Take Oath At Monticello, Feeling The Weight of the Past

docs.abstract: Mr. Azar, a former drug company executive, immediately confronts two huge challenges: how to rein in drug prices and how to administer the Affordable Care Act.
docs.snippet: Mr. Azar, a former drug company executive, immediately confronts two huge challenges: how to rein in drug prices and how to administer the Affordable Care Act.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate confirmed Alex M. Azar II on Wednesday to be secretary of health and human services, clearing the way for President Trump’s second health secretary to begin controlling more than a trillion dollars a year in spending on medical insurance coverage for about one-third of all Americans.

headline.main: Senate Confirms Trump Nominee Alex Azar as Health Secretary
headline.print_headline: After Questions About Rising Drug Prices, Senate Confirms Pick for Health Dept.

docs.abstract: Health officials complain that pharmaceutical companies refuse to share samples needed to develop affordable generic versions of brand-name medicines.
docs.snippet: Health officials complain that pharmaceutical companies refuse to share samples needed to develop affordable generic versions of brand-name medicines.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Trump administration officials, seeking ways to lower drug costs, are targeting pharmaceutical companies that refuse to provide samples of their products to generic drug companies, making it impossible to create inexpensive generic copies of a brand-name medicine.

headline.main: Drug Company ‘Shenanigans’ to Block Generics Come Under Federal Scrutiny
headline.print_headline: Drug Company ‘Shenanigans’ to Dodge Generics Come Under Scrutiny

docs.abstract: The secretary of health and human services dismissed solutions that have long been supported by Democrats, but that President Trump endorsed during the 2016 campaign.
docs.snippet: The secretary of health and human services dismissed solutions that have long been supported by Democrats, but that President Trump endorsed during the 2016 campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration hit back on Monday against critics of President Trump’s plan to reduce prescription drug prices, saying his ideas would be far more effective than remedies championed by Democrats.

headline.main: Trump Administration Defends Plan to Lower Prescription Drug Prices
headline.print_headline: Administration Defends Plan For Lowering Drug Prices

docs.abstract: A ruling allowing more hospitals to seek more money was based on evidence that the government had been using faulty data to calculate costs for decades.
docs.snippet: A ruling allowing more hospitals to seek more money was based on evidence that the government had been using faulty data to calculate costs for decades.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A federal appeals court has cleared the way for hospitals around the country to seek more money from Medicare, based on evidence that the government has been using faulty data to calculate costs for decades.

headline.main: Hospitals Challenge Medicare Payments, With Help From Judge Kavanaugh
headline.print_headline: Hospitals Protest Medicare Outlay, With Help from Court Nominee

docs.abstract: Federal officials said they would support state efforts to require able-bodied adults to work as a condition of eligibility for Medicaid.
docs.snippet: Federal officials said they would support state efforts to require able-bodied adults to work as a condition of eligibility for Medicaid.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration said on Thursday that it would allow states to impose work requirements in Medicaid, a major policy shift that moves toward fulfilling a conservative vision for one of the nation’s largest social insurance programs for low-income people.

headline.main: Trump Administration Says States May Impose Work Requirements for Medicaid
headline.print_headline: U.S. Supports Requiring Work To Get Medicaid
